result.execSummary:
The defendant Michael A Millard was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Michael A Millard is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Michael A Millard was found guilty of Battery - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Repeater, Domestic Abuse Repeater], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Consecutive to: Sentence serving in Jackson County Case No. 14CF60.

superMiscConds.notes: Outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If reconfined or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  Pay the costs of supervision.  DNA surcharge not ordered.
Defendant shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, with the victim, her residence or her family.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent, including but not limited to, domestic violence programming.  

Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.

Comply with all extended supervision conditions ordered in 14CF60.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, and with Attorney Covey.  Defendant plead no contest to count 3.  Court advised the defendant of the charge and possible penalties he plead to. Firearm warning given.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements of the charge with the defendant.  Defendant understood.    Defense stipulates to a factual basis for the plea to count 3.  Court confirmed defendant's prior convictions.  Court finds the that defendant has entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights freely, voluntarily and intelligently.  Found guilty of Count 3.  Counts 1 and 2 dismissed.  Victim spoke to the court.  State requests  3 years initial confinement, with 1 year of extended supervision.   DV programming.  No contact with the victim or her family.  Defense made sentencing argument.  Requests 1 year consecutive to any other sentence.  Defendant did not elect to exercise his right to allocution.  Court ordered:  30 mo. initial confinement, with 6 mo. of extended supervision.  Consecutive to 14CF60.   DV programming.  No contact with the victim, her residence, or her family. Same conditions as 14CF60.  Eligible SAP.  Not eligible for CIP.  CC & costs of supervision. No DNA surcharge ordered.  Zero days of credit.

Covers case No. 14CF72 and 14CF60.  If released, must be equipped with GPS monitoring devise.    Until further order of the court, you shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, except through your attorney, with the victims in 14CF60 and 14CF72.    Until further order of the court you shall not leave the State of Wisconsin, Jackson or Clark County.  Must remain at parents home, except for legal and medical appointments.

Covers Case No. 14CF60 and 14CF72.    Until further order of the court, you shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, except through your attorney, with any of the following individuals:  A.A.K.
Per Mary Miller - STC on 8-26-15 and STC on 9-16-15 can be taken off calendar.

Final Pre-trial on 14CF60:  Defendant appeared in custody with counsel Michael Covey.  ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defense confirms that the Demand for Discover and Inspection filed in September has been complied with except regarding the expert witness.  DA Inlow states they haven't received any documents but have witness list.  Attorney Covey states there is no new evidence but he may have a couple of civil witnesses (defendant's parents) that may testify and he objects to request to file a written summary of testimony.  DA Inlow states there is no need to file the summary.  Court orders:  #1 - will reserve finding as the Court first wants to watch the entire video testimony; granted exclusion for victim to be present during trial; Grants exclusion for witness to be present during trial but will re-visit witness issues regarding period of incarceration; Court will reserve ruling on #12; Court will allow recorded testimony to be played; DA is to supply all information to defense regarding testimony of witness within 10 days prior to trial date.  14CF72 is backup trial.

Defendant appeared with counsel Michael Covery.  Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  14CF60 is to be set for a 3-day jury trial and FPT.  14CF70 is a backup to that trial but will also be set for trial at a later date.  Bond continued.
